I would check out CTRE’s docs on SysId and WPILib’s docs on SysId, which are what really helped me understand it.

To give a basic overview, system identification or SysId is a way of recording and analyzing a mechanism’s response to a given input. This involves quasistatic and dynamic routines. Quasistatic routines give a constant voltage to a motor, and dynamic routines give increasing voltage over time. The mechanism’s position is logged, and you can analyze it with the SysId application that comes with WPILib.

CTRE very nicely provides pre-made SysId routines that are in CommandSwerveDrivetrain.java. You can simply set the m_sysIdRoutineToApply variable to whichever routine you want to run, and then you can see the button bindings in configureBindings in RobotContainer.java that you press to run the routines.

If I understand you correctly, you need to use the built in CTRE commands to run the SysId routines, and you can download and convert the logs (from .hoot to .wpilog) in Tuner X, then use the “SysId 2025” application to load the downloaded log files (.wpilog) and analyze them to get your constants and such.

The CTRE documentation details how to use Tuner X to download and convert the logs, and the WPILib documentation shows how to use the SysId application.

modules are shaking when we are enabled?

On the ground or when propped up? Since the PID need to be tuned to overcome friction with the ground to be able to steer it is normal for swerves to have some jitter if the wheels aren’t touching the ground.
